05854nam a22007455i 9780804792226DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202014cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2014007328  a97808047922267 a10.1515/97808047922262doi  a(DE-B1597)564728  a(OCoLC)1198929967  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aBV3570b.B37 2014 7aHIS0090002bisacsh1 aBaron, Beth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Orphan Scandal :bChristian Missionaries and the Rise of the Muslim Brotherhood /cBeth Baron. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tCast of Characters -- tPrologue: The Turkiyya Hasan Affair -- t1. Forgotten Children: Caring for the Orphaned and Abandoned -- t2. Winning Souls for Christ: American Presbyterians in Cairo -- t3. Speaking in Tongues: Pentecostal Revival in Asyut -- t4. Nothing Less Than a Miracle: The Swedish Salaam Mission of Port Said -- t5. Fight Them with Their Own Weapons: The Origins of the Muslim Brotherhood -- t6. Combating Conversion: The Expansion of the Anti-Missionary Movement -- t7. Crackdown: Suppressing the League for the Defense of Islam -- t8. The Battle for Egypt's Orphans: Toward a Muslim Welfare State -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOn a sweltering June morning in 1933 a fifteen-year-old Muslim orphan girl refused to rise in a show of respect for her elders at her Christian missionary school in Port Said. Her intransigence led to a beating-and to the end of most foreign missions in Egypt-and contributed to the rise of Islamist organizations. Turkiyya Hasan left the Swedish Salaam Mission with scratches on her legs and a suitcase of evidence of missionary misdeeds. Her story hit a nerve among Egyptians, and news of the beating quickly spread through the country. Suspicion of missionary schools, hospitals, and homes increased, and a vehement anti-missionary movement swept the country. That missionaries had won few converts was immaterial to Egyptian observers: stories such as Turkiyya's showed that the threat to Muslims and Islam was real. This is a great story of unintended consequences: Christian missionaries came to Egypt to convert and provide social services for children. Their actions ultimately inspired the development of the Muslim Brotherhood and similar Islamist groups. In The Orphan Scandal, Beth Baron provides a new lens through which to view the rise of Islamic groups in Egypt. This fresh perspective offers a starting point to uncover hidden links between Islamic activists and a broad cadre of Protestant evangelicals. Exploring the historical aims of the Christian missions and the early efforts of the Muslim Brotherhood, Baron shows how the Muslim Brotherhood and like-minded Islamist associations developed alongside and in reaction to the influx of missionaries. Patterning their organization and social welfare projects on the early success of the Christian missions, the Brotherhood launched their own efforts to "save" children and provide for the orphaned, abandoned, and poor. In battling for Egypt's children, Islamic activists created a network of social welfare institutions and a template for social action across the country-the effects of which, we now know, would only gain power and influence across the country in the decades to come.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aChristianity and other religionsxIslamxHistoryx20th centuryxEgyptxHistory. 0aChristianity and other religionsxIslamxHistoryy20th century. 0aIslamxRelationsxChristianityxHistoryx2